<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="50" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[685,1173,449,1479]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,813,449,470]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Basal 2/3 of elytra testaceous, with two black, narrow, angular lines; distal third of elytra black, with a large orange spot. These characteristics will distinguish the members of this species from its congeners.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="50" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[685,1173,449,1479]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,916,581,602]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Redescription. Size:</emphasis>
Length 13.0 mm; width 5.0 mm. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[768,832,608,629]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Form:</emphasis>
As in 
<figureCitation box="[893,963,608,629]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="13.[197,236,1681,1700]" captionTargetBox="[215,1153,196,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-0@13.[210,1155,194,1665]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs. 41–44. Possible Batesian mimicry. 41) Lasiodera kirbyi; 42) Enoclerus obliquevittis; 43) Haplomutilla spinosa (Mutillidae); 44) Ameris dufresnii (Curculionidae)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5334322" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5334322/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[971,1036,608,629]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Color:</emphasis>
Mostly black, except 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[765,777,629,643]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">st</superScript>
3 antennomeres testaceous ventrally, and elytra tricolored, basal 2/3 of elytra testaceous, with 2 narrow black angular lines, distal third of elytra black, with large circular orange spot. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1049,1111,714,735]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Head:</emphasis>
Frons vested with patch of white setae, epicranium densely vested with black setae; funicular antennomeres filiform, antennomeres 9 and 10 triangular, antennomere 11 sublunulate (
<figureCitation box="[1081,1160,821,842]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,214,1572,1591]" captionTargetBox="[156,1167,196,1555]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[154,1169,194,1556]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 20–26. Lasiodera species. Antennae: 20) L. trifasciata; 21) L. kirby; 22) L. ruficollis. Pronota: 23) L. kirbyi;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5334300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5334300/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
); eyes small, much narrower than width of frons (EW/ FW = 55/120); cranium finely punctate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[685,769,900,921]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Thorax:</emphasis>
Pronotum slightly oblong (PW/PL = 120/125), side margin with tubercle (
<figureCitation box="[1080,1160,927,948]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,214,1572,1591]" captionTargetBox="[156,1167,196,1555]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[154,1169,194,1556]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 20–26. Lasiodera species. Antennae: 20) L. trifasciata; 21) L. kirby; 22) L. ruficollis. Pronota: 23) L. kirbyi;" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5334300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5334300/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
); elytral disc without asetiferous punctures, slightly tumescent at base, slightly depressed in middle third; EL/EW = 295/90; anterior protibial margin roughened. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[949,1060,1033,1054]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Abdomen:</emphasis>
Pygidium scutiform; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[963,1042,1060,1081]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="11.[197,236,1295,1314]" captionTargetBox="[178,1188,207,1260]" captionTargetId="figure-164@11.[175,1190,194,1279]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs. 35–38. Lasiodera species, abdominal terminalia. 35) L. kirbyi; 36) L. ruficollis; 37) L. rufipes; 38) L. trifasciata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5334314" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5334314/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
; phallobasic rod quadripartite
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[685,1173,449,1479]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,811,1113,1134]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Variation.</emphasis>
Length 16.0–17.5 mm; width 4.3–6.5 mm. Other than body size, the available specimens are quite homogeneous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[685,1173,449,1479]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,876,1193,1214]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Natural History.</emphasis>
This species, in consort with a species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gahan" authorityName="Gahan" authorityYear="1910" box="[796,965,1218,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Enoclerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[796,892,1218,1240]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Enoclerus</emphasis>
Gahan
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[983,1059,1219,1240]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="13.[197,236,1681,1700]" captionTargetBox="[215,1153,196,1662]" captionTargetId="figure-0@13.[210,1155,194,1665]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs. 41–44. Possible Batesian mimicry. 41) Lasiodera kirbyi; 42) Enoclerus obliquevittis; 43) Haplomutilla spinosa (Mutillidae); 44) Ameris dufresnii (Curculionidae)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5334322" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5334322/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
), is clearly involved in a Batesian mimetic relationship with the velvet ant 
<emphasis box="[791,1000,1271,1293]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Haplomutilla spinosa</emphasis>
(Swederus) (
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[799,902,1299,1320]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Mutillidae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="50" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[685,1173,449,1479]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,838,1325,1346]" pageId="6" pageNumber="50">Distribution.</emphasis>
